[b]The Cartographer's Mistake[/b]
[i]A short test story for PawPoller QA[/i]

By Test Author

[hr]

The map was wrong, and Eda had drawn it.

She found the error in the second week, when the river they had been
following was supposed to bend north-east and instead bent
[i]south[/i]-east. The line on the page was confident. The river
disagreed. The river was bigger than the line.

[hr]

That evening she pinned the map to the inside of the tent and looked
at it for a long time. The mistake was small in any objective sense
&mdash; a few millimetres of confident ink — but the river had been
there for ten thousand years, and the map for six months. There was
no honest way to argue with that.

In the morning she rolled the map up, put it away, and started a new
one.

You can read more about Eda's expedition in [url=https://example.com/]
the official record[/url], which corrects this and three other errors
that nobody had thought to check.

[i]End of The Cartographer's Mistake[/i]
